{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 instrument. For example, an entity may amend its charter under typical state nonprofit corporation laws if it follows certain procedures.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F34398601898_ID0EOWAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F34398601898_ID0EOWAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F34398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
34
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Although an amendment is generally not effective unless the entity observes the statutory procedures, the state does not normally undertake a substantive review of the proposed amendments under the typical statute.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F35398601898_ID0ETWAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F35398601898_ID0ETWAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F35398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
35
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 In contrast, under the common law of charitable trusts, unless the trust instrument provides otherwise, deviations from the terms of trust typically require court approval.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F36398601898_ID0EXWAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F36398601898_ID0EXWAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F36398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
36
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E5WAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E5WAG_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
3. The Static Charter Fidelity Norm
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EIXAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EIXAG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The \u8220\'3fstatic charter fidelity norm\u8221\'3f requires fiduciaries to \u8220\'3fensure that a charity operates in accordance with its governing instrument--as it was originally drafted and as it may be amended only with the [ex ante] substantive approval of a governmental actor.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F37398601898_ID0EZXAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F37398601898_ID0EZXAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F37398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
37
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 It is important to note that this is the 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
static
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 charter fidelity norm, thus emphasizing that charity fiduciaries cannot unilaterally deviate from the terms of their charter merely by following certain procedures. Rather, they may amend charter purposes and act in accordance with amended charter terms only if a governmental actor (typically a court) authorizes such action after substantively reviewing the justifiability of a proposed change to the charity\rquote s governing instrument.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F38398601898_ID0ECYAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F38398601898_ID0ECYAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F38398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
38
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EJYAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EJYAG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The static charter fidelity norm typically governs charitable trusts.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F39398601898_ID0ERYAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F39398601898_ID0ERYAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F39398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
39
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Therefore, if a charitable trust is formed for the express purpose of treating people suffering from a particular disease, but medical advances render the charity\rquote s fulfillment of this purpose impossible or impracticable, the charity\rquote s trustees may petition a court in a cy pres proceeding to authorize the trust to fulfill a different charitable purpose.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F40398601898_ID0EWYAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F40398601898_ID0EWYAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F40398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
40
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 In such a case, the trustees are subject to the static charter fidelity norm because they are not authorized to alter the purposes of the trust without first petitioning a court.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E6YAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E6YAG_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_923_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_923_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*923
}
}
}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
4. The Dynamic Mission Fidelity Norm
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0ENZAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0ENZAG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The term \u8220\'3fdynamic mission fidelity norm\u8221\'3f reflects \u8220\'3fa requirement that fiduciaries cause their charities to operate in accordance with the charities\rquote  precise charitable mission(s) as the governing board expands, contracts, or otherwise alters the mission(s) from time to time.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F41398601898_ID0E5ZAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F41398601898_ID0E5ZAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F41398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
41
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 In this context, \u8220\'3f\u8220\'3fcharitable mission\u8221\'3f refers to the specific charitable objectives that a charity maintains in carrying out its customarily broader purposes articulated in the purposes clause of its governing instrument.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F42398601898_ID0ED1AG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F42398601898_ID0ED1AG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F42398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
42
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 For example, consider an entity organized for \u8220\'3fcharitable purposes,\u8221\'3f including \u8220\'3fthe purpose of benefiting the community by providing health care and promoting the health\u8221\'3f of residents of a certain geographic region. Assume that the entity\rquote s board has resolved to create and operate a children\rquote s hospital in furtherance of the entity\rquote s charter purposes. Operation of the children\rquote s hospital is the mission of the entity. Under the dynamic mission fidelity norm, the governing board is free to alter the mission of the entity over time (for example, by resolving to turn the children\rquote s hospital into a general hospital), but the board must govern the entity so as to advance whatever mission is in place until the board has officially changed that mission.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E51AG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E51AG_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
5. The Historic Mission Fidelity Norm
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EI2AG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EI2AG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
As an alternative to advancing the dynamic mission fidelity norm, the law could require fiduciaries to ensure that \u8220\'3ftheir charities [] operate in accordance with the charities\rquote  precise historic missions, which may be far more limited than the purposes for which they are expressly organized under their governing instruments\u8221\'3f--the \u8220\'3fhistoric mission fidelity norm.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F43398601898_ID0EV2AG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F43398601898_ID0EV2AG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F43398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
43
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Under this norm, deviating from the historic mission of the charity requires ex ante substantive approval from a governmental actor.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F44398601898_ID0E12AG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F44398601898_ID0E12AG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F44398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
44
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Thus, consider the example of the children\rquote s hospital. If fiduciaries are bound by the historic mission fidelity norm, they may not turn the children\rquote s hospital into a general hospital simply by resolving to do so. Rather, they must first seek approval from an appropriate state official or body (most likely a court) to change the entity\rquote s mission, even though the purposes articulated in the entity\rquote s charter are plainly broad enough to encompass operating a general hospital.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EM3AG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EM3AG_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
6. The Charity Advancement Norm
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EW3AG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EW3AG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Perhaps the most basic obedience norm, upon which all others rest, is what this Article shall term the \u8220\'3fcharity advancement norm.\u8221\'3f As charity fiduciaries 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_924_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_924_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*924
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 seek to forge a clear charitable path for their entities, their choices are determined in part by state law\rquote s imposition of charter fidelity and mission fidelity norms. Although there is some variance as to the specificity and mutability of charitable purposes vis-\u224\'3f-vis obedience norms, all of the norms require \u8220\'3fthat charity fiduciaries act so as to advance charitable purposes.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F45398601898_ID0ES4AG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F45398601898_ID0ES4AG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F45398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
45
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Each norm discussed requires fiduciaries to \u8220\'3fdrive\u8221\'3f charities in a \u8220\'3fgeneral charitable direction.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F46398601898_ID0EX4AG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F46398601898_ID0EX4AG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F46398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
46
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Consequently, a constitutive norm underlying the others may be called the \u8220\'3fcharity advancement norm.\u8221\'3f
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EA5AG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EA5AG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The charity advancement norm implies a restraint, which prohibits charity fiduciaries from primarily advancing a 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
non-charitable
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 purpose.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F47398601898_ID0EK5AG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F47398601898_ID0EK5AG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F47398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
47
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The restraint is simply the negative corollary of the norm itself. The negative corollary of the charity advancement norm, like the norm proper, is constitutive of other obedience norms. A course of action by charity fiduciaries that violates the negative corollary of the charity advancement norm would generally also betray the other obedience norms identified in this Article, such as the dynamic charter fidelity, static charter fidelity, historic mission fidelity, and dynamic mission fidelity norms.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F48398601898_ID0EV5AG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F48398601898_ID0EV5AG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F48398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
48
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Furthermore, the negative corollary of the charity advancement norm and the legality norm reinforce one another, because operating illegally is generally inconsistent with advancing only charitable purposes.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F49398601898_ID0EZ5AG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F49398601898_ID0EZ5AG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F49398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
49
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EA6AG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EA6AG_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
C. Contexts for Applying Obedience Norms
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EK6AG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EK6AG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Obedience norms apply in a variety of circumstances. The following discussion identifies several of these contexts.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F50398601898_ID0EU6AG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F50398601898_ID0EU6AG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F50398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
50
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E26AG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E26AG_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
1. Daily Operations
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EFABG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EFABG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Obedience norms limit the options available to fiduciaries as they oversee 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_925_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_925_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*925
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 the charity\rquote s routine operations.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F51398601898_ID0ESABG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F51398601898_ID0ESABG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F51398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
51
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 For example, the legality norm requires fiduciaries to manage the charity so as to ensure that it operates lawfully.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F52398601898_ID0EXABG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F52398601898_ID0EXABG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F52398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
52
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Similarly, charter fidelity norms constrain charitable choices contemplated by charity managers, and mission fidelity norms prevent a charity from straying from a pre-approved charitable pathway as it conducts daily operations.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EABBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EABBG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Certain obedience norms not only preclude charity managers from advancing illegitimate purposes, but also require them to act positively.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F53398601898_ID0EIBBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F53398601898_ID0EIBBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F53398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
53
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 For example, the charity advancement norm requires fiduciaries to oversee the charity\rquote s operations to ensure that it indeed serves a charitable purpose.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F54398601898_ID0ENBBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F54398601898_ID0ENBBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F54398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
54
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The charter fidelity norms can be understood to impose a duty on charity managers to manage their charity so that it actually fulfills the purposes set forth in its charter.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F55398601898_ID0ESBBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F55398601898_ID0ESBBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F55398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
55
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Similarly, the mission fidelity norms may be seen as requiring charity fiduciaries to ensure that their charity carries out its specific charitable mission.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F56398601898_ID0EWBBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F56398601898_ID0EWBBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F56398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
56
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E4BBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E4BBG_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
2. Formal Amendments to Charter
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EHCBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EHCBG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
A state\rquote s choice between the two charter fidelity norms determines the ease with which a charity can amend its governing instrument.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F57398601898_ID0EPCBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F57398601898_ID0EPCBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F57398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
57
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Under the dynamic charter fidelity norm, a charity can amend its governing instrument, including its purposes clause, much more easily than a charity constrained by the static charter fidelity norm. Under the latter, fiduciaries who wish to change the terms of the charity\rquote s governing instrument must first receive permission from a governmental actor, such as a court--permission that may be granted only after the governmental actor has reviewed the justifiability of the change. The dynamic charter fidelity norm, in contrast, allows fiduciaries to amend the charity\rquote s charter without first submitting the change to state actors for substantive review.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F58398601898_ID0EZCBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F58398601898_ID0EZCBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F58398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
58
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EADBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EADBG_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_926_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_926_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*926
}
}
}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
3. Use of Funds to Further Post-Amendment Charter Purposes or a New Mission
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EODBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EODBG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Changes to a charity\rquote s purposes clause and modifications to a charity\rquote s mission present a very interesting legal issue: May funds held by the charity prior to the change in charter purposes (or mission) be used to further the charity\rquote s new charter purposes (or new mission)?
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F59398601898_ID0EXDBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F59398601898_ID0EXDBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F59398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
59
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 To articulate this issue is to recognize that the choice of charter fidelity norm, as well as the choice of mission fidelity norm, affects much more than merely the method by which charity fiduciaries can initiate changes to the charity\rquote s formal purposes and mission.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EAEBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EAEBG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
To illustrate, assume that the dynamic charter fidelity norm governs formal amendments to a charity\rquote s governing instrument. Under this norm, as long as the charity\rquote s governing board follows the procedures set forth in state statutory law, the board is free to alter the express purposes for which the charity is organized. However, that the dynamic charter fidelity norm governs the charity\rquote s formal ability to amend its charter does not necessarily mandate that the dynamic charter fidelity norm governs the charity\rquote s ability to use pre-amendment assets to further post-amendment purposes. Conceivably, state law could instead apply the static charter fidelity norm to the post-charter-amendment use of assets held before the charter amendment.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F60398601898_ID0EREBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F60398601898_ID0EREBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F60398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
60
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Similarly, a legal question arises as to whether the charity can devote assets held prior to the change in mission to advance its new mission, even if a formal charter amendment is not necessary when the governing board changes the charity\rquote s mission. The charity would not be free to do so if the historic mission fidelity norm, rather than the dynamic mission fidelity norm, governs the use of assets held prior to the change in mission.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F61398601898_ID0EYEBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F61398601898_ID0EYEBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F61398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
61
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E6EBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E6EBG_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
4. Distributions in Dissolution and Liquidation of a Charity
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EJFBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EJFBG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
A related issue is whether a charity seeking to dissolve itself may, pursuant to a plan of dissolution, transfer its assets to another charity with a mission different from that in its own charter.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F62398601898_ID0ERFBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F62398601898_ID0ERFBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F62398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
62
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 If the state statute governing distributions in dissolution expressly requires the dissolving entity to transfer its assets to other charities with purposes similar to the longstanding express 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_927_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_927_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*927
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 purposes of the dissolving entity,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F63398601898_ID0EZFBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F63398601898_ID0EZFBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F63398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
63
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 the statute at least partially embraces the static charter fidelity norm. The transferee must devote assets received from the dissolving entity in accordance with the transferee\rquote s charter--one that sets forth purposes similar to those of the dissolving entity\rquote s charter. In effect, because the two entities have similar charter purposes, such a state statute requires vicarious fidelity to the dissolved entity\rquote s charter.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EIGBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EIGBG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
If, however, the state statute does not explicitly require a dissolving entity to distribute assets to only charitable transferees with similar purposes,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F64398601898_ID0EOGBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F64398601898_ID0EOGBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F64398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
64
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 the state courts must decide whether to employ common law trust concepts to compel such a result. To empower directors to authorize distributions in dissolution to a charity with purposes dissimilar to those of the dissolving charity effectively enables directors to select new charter terms that will govern distributed assets. Hence, directors with such authority are functioning under the dynamic charter fidelity norm. In contrast, if the courts require the dissolving entity to distribute assets to a charity with a similar purpose, the courts, in part, embrace the static charter fidelity norm in the context of dissolution and liquidation.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F65398601898_ID0E3GBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F65398601898_ID0E3GBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F65398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
65
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Similarly, if courts specifically require the transferee entity to operate similarly to the liquidating entity, the court embraces the historic mission fidelity norm.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EFHBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EFHBG_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
D. Co-Existence of Obedience Norms
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EPHBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EPHBG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Some of these obedience norms can co-exist together, while others are incompatible.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F66398601898_ID0EXHBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F66398601898_ID0EXHBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F66398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
66
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The legality norm is consistent to some degree with every other norm, although it establishes boundaries for a charity\rquote s express charter purposes and mission. The dynamic charter fidelity norm and the static charter fidelity norm are mutually exclusive in any single context, as are the historic mission fidelity norm and the dynamic mission fidelity norm.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EDIBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EDIBG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
However, to embrace one of the charter norms to the exclusion of the other does not necessarily require one to adopt its most analogous mission fidelity norm. Thus, theoretically, a state that has adopted the static charter fidelity norm need not necessarily adopt the historic mission fidelity norm. A charity\rquote s proposed change in mission may be quite consistent with broadly-phrased charter purposes. The static charter fidelity norm limits the range of options available to directors seeking to alter a charity\rquote s mission, but it does not literally compel adherence to any specific mission.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F67398601898_ID0EUIBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F67398601898_ID0EUIBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F67398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
67
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 In contrast, to embrace the dynamic charter fidelity norm in one context virtually requires rejection of the historic mission fidelity norm in the same context. For example, if 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_928_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_928_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*928
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 directors are duty-bound to follow the charity\rquote s historic mission after a charter amendment to grant them formal authority to amend general charter purposes seems rather pointless.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EFJBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EFJBG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Finally, norms that are mutually exclusive in the same context are not necessarily mutually exclusive when applied in different contexts. Thus, one theoretically could embrace the dynamic charter fidelity norm in the context of formally approving charter amendments, but favor the static charter fidelity norm as applied to the post-amendment use of funds held by the charity both before and after the amendment, or as applied to distributions in liquidation of the charity.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EUJBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EUJBG_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
II. 
}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
Obedience Norms Governing Trustees of Charitable Trusts
\par 
}
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E6JBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E6JBG_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
A. Trust Law in General
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EJKBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EJKBG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
From the perspective of trustees, the law of private trusts largely subsumes the norm of static charter fidelity, circumscribed by the legality norm.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EVKBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EVKBG_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
1. The Charter Fidelity Norm Under General Trust Law
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E6KBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E6KBG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Under the Restatement (Third) of Trusts, a trustee \u8220\'3fhas a duty to administer the trust, diligently and in good faith, in accordance with the terms of trust and applicable law.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F68398601898_ID0EQLBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F68398601898_ID0EQLBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F68398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
68
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The official Comment to the Restatement refers to the duty as \u8220\'3f[t]he normal duty of a trustee to obey the terms of trust.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F69398601898_ID0E5LBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F69398601898_ID0E5LBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F69398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
69
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Although a trust can often be amended with the consent of all beneficiaries (or, in some cases, with the consent of the beneficiaries and the settlor),
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F70398601898_ID0EBMBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F70398601898_ID0EBMBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F70398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
70
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 a trustee who believes an amendment is prudent generally may not unilaterally amend the trust instrument absent explicit authority in the trust instrument to do so.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F71398601898_ID0EGMBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F71398601898_ID0EGMBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F71398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
71
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 A petition for judicial modification of the trust must be filed, and relief is available only in limited circumstances.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F72398601898_ID0ELMBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F72398601898_ID0ELMBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F72398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
72
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 To require a trustee to obey the terms of trust is, of course, to require \u8220\'3fcharter fidelity.\u8221\'3f Further, to permit trustees to act contrary to those terms only by petitioning a court to authorize a trust amendment is to embrace the static charter fidelity norm.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EXMBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EXMBG_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_929_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_929_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*929
}
}
}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
2. The Legality Norm
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EFNBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EFNBG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The law of trusts also embraces the legality norm by invalidating trust terms that are illegal or contrary to public policy.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F73398601898_ID0ENNBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F73398601898_ID0ENNBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F73398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
73
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Moreover, a trustee is not under a duty to comply with a trust provision that is unlawful or contrary to public policy; indeed, the trustee is generally under a duty 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
not
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 to comply with such a provision.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F74398601898_ID0ETNBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F74398601898_ID0ETNBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F74398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
74
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E1NBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E1NBG_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
B. Charitable Trust Law
\par 
}
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EEOBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EEOBG_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
1. The Charity Advancement Norm
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EOOBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EOOBG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Trust law permits the creation of charitable trusts, which, unlike private trusts, are not formed primarily to benefit identified or ascertainable beneficiaries.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F75398601898_ID0EWOBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F75398601898_ID0EWOBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F75398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
75
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 A trust\rquote s purpose is considered charitable \u8220\'3fif its accomplishment is of such social interest or benefit to the community as to justify permitting the property to be devoted to the purpose in perpetuity and to justify the various other special privileges that are typically allowed to charitable trusts.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F76398601898_ID0EEPBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F76398601898_ID0EEPBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F76398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
76
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 A trust can be \u8220\'3fcharitable\u8221\'3f even if it does not designate a particular charitable purpose or mode for achieving charitable purposes.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F77398601898_ID0EJPBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F77398601898_ID0EJPBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F77398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
77
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Thus, a trust organized simply for \u8220\'3fcharitable purposes\u8221\'3f is a charitable trust.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F78398601898_ID0ESPBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F78398601898_ID0ESPBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F78398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
78
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E3PBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E3PBG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Almost tautologically, to require a trustee to administer a \u8220\'3fcharitable\u8221\'3f trust according to its terms is to implement the charity advancement norm. Charitable trusts are accorded special treatment in virtue of their \u8220\'3fcharitable purposes\u8221\'3f expressed in the terms of trust, according to which trustees must administer their trusts.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F79398601898_ID0EMQBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F79398601898_ID0EMQBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F79398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
79
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Therefore, to require a trustee to administer a charitable trust according to its terms is to compel adherence to the charity advancement norm.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EYQBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EYQBG_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_930_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_930_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*930
}
}
}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
2. Cy Pres, Equitable Deviation, the Legality Norm, and the Static Charter Fidelity Norm
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EGRBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EGRBG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Charitable trusts are also governed by the legality and static charter fidelity norms. The terms of charitable trusts, like other trusts, must not be unlawful,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F80398601898_ID0EPRBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F80398601898_ID0EPRBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F80398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
80
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 and their trustees generally must obey lawful trust terms.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F81398601898_ID0EURBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F81398601898_ID0EURBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F81398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
81
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The law of charitable trusts also embraces both the legality and static charter fidelity norms through the doctrines of cy pres and equitable deviation. The doctrine of cy pres allows trustees to deviate from the dispositive terms of a charitable trust only in limited circumstances, and only with advance judicial approval.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F82398601898_ID0E3RBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F82398601898_ID0E3RBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F82398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
82
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Under the traditional doctrine of cy pres, a court may direct charity fiduciaries to apply charitable trust funds to purposes similar to the original trust purposes if accomplishing the original purposes becomes impossible, impracticable, or illegal, as long as the transferor of the funds has manifested an intent to devote the funds to charitable purposes more general than the frustrated specific charitable purpose.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F83398601898_ID0EBSBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F83398601898_ID0EBSBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F83398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
83
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Restatement (Third) of Trusts and the Uniform Trust Code generally follows the traditional doctrine of cy pres, but adds wastefulness to the grounds for applying the doctrine and presumes that a donor possesses general charitable intent.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F84398601898_ID0EFSBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F84398601898_ID0EFSBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F84398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
84
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EMSBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EMSBG_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_931_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_931_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*931
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Closely related to the doctrine of cy pres is the doctrine of deviation (or \u8220\'3fequitable deviation\u8221\'3f). This latter doctrine empowers a court to direct a trustee of a charitable trust to deviate from the administrative terms of a trust if compliance with the original terms is impossible or illegal, or if compliance with the terms of trust would substantially impede the accomplishment of trust purposes on account of circumstances that the settlor did not foresee.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F85398601898_ID0E1SBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F85398601898_ID0E1SBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F85398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
85
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EBTBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EBTBG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In summary, unless the original charitable purposes fail on account of illegality, impossibility, impracticability, or wastefulness, trustees of charitable trusts must obey the express charitable purposes for which the settlor created the trust. Further, if the trustees believe that the grounds for applying cy pres exist, they must petition a court before straying from the express terms of trust. A similar rule applies if trustees wish to depart from the administrative terms of trust. The default rules governing charitable trusts thereby adopt a strong form of the static charter fidelity norm, as limited by the legality norm.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EWTBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EWTBG_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
3. Mission Fidelity
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EAUBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EAUBG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The common law of charitable trusts does not appear to articulate any mission fidelity norm that is distinct from static charter fidelity. Of course, the trustees of a charitable trust are generally bound by the terms of trust, as expressed in the trust instrument. A charitable trust may be drafted so as to articulate a very specific charitable purpose, one that might qualify as a charitable \u8220\'3fmission,\u8221\'3f as the term is commonly employed. A trustee desiring to alter that specific mission must petition a court in cy pres proceedings and establish the grounds for applying the doctrine.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F86398601898_ID0ERUBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F86398601898_ID0ERUBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F86398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
86
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The salient fact is that any such action is necessary only when the charitable \u8220\'3fmission\u8221\'3f is articulated in the trust instrument. The doctrine of cy pres applies only when \u8220\'3fproperty is placed in trust to be applied to a designated charitable purpose.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F87398601898_ID0ECVBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F87398601898_ID0ECVBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F87398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
87
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 If no \u8220\'3fdesignated\u8221\'3f charitable purpose fails, there is no basis for petitioning a court to amend the terms of the charitable trust. Accordingly, the common law doctrine of cy pres does not contemplate judicial scrutiny of mere changes in charitable mission that fall within the scope of broad charitable purposes articulated in the trust instrument.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EOVBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EOVBG_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_932_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_932_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*932
}
}
}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 III. 
}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
Obedience Norms Governing Directors of Charitable Nonprofit Corporations
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E4VBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E4VBG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The typical nonprofit corporation statute imposes no express \u8220\'3fduty of obedience\u8221\'3f on directors of charitable nonprofit corporations.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F88398601898_ID0EFWBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F88398601898_ID0EFWBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F88398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
88
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Nonetheless, state nonprofit laws embrace a variety of obedience norms.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EOWBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EOWBG_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
A. The Legality Norm
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EYWBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EYWBG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Nonprofit corporations, like other entities, are typically required to act in accordance with the law.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F89398601898_ID0EAXBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F89398601898_ID0EAXBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F89398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
89
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Fiduciaries who deliberately cause an entity to act unlawfully would presumably breach their statutory fiduciary duties.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F90398601898_ID0EFXBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F90398601898_ID0EFXBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F90398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
90
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Consequently, state corporation laws embrace the legality norm.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EOXBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EOXBG_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
B. Charter Fidelity Norms
\par 
}
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EYXBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EYXBG_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
1. In General
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EKYBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EKYBG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
State nonprofit corporation laws also adopt norms of charter fidelity. Directors of a nonprofit charitable corporation must not cause the entity they govern to act contrary to its corporate purposes.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F91398601898_ID0EVYBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F91398601898_ID0EVYBG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F91398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
