3. What Charter Fidelity Norm Governs the Use of Assets Held Before and After a Charter Amendment?
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EL4BG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EL4BG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
An issue that tests the bounds of obedience norms is whether a charity may use assets held prior to a charter amendment--as well as substitutes or replacements for those assets--to fulfill post-amendment purposes. A state law prohibiting a charity from using its assets (and replacements thereof) held prior to the charter amendment to advance post-amendment purposes implements the static charter fidelity norm as to the management of pre-amendment funds and their substitutes.
}
