{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
4. What Charter Fidelity Norm Governs the Distribution of Assets in Dissolution and Liquidation of a Charitable Nonprofit Corporation?
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EODBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EODBI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
A related issue is whether a charity desiring to terminate its existence may, pursuant to a plan of dissolution, transfer its assets to a charity with purposes dissimilar to those expressed in its charter. Some state statutes require dissolving charities to distribute assets to organizations having charitable purposes similar to those of the dissolving entity.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F189398601898_ID0EZDBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F189398601898_ID0EZDBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F189398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
189
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Other statutes provide simply that the corporation must distribute its assets to other tax-exempt charities or governmental bodies.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F190398601898_ID0E5DBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F190398601898_ID0E5DBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F190398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
190
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 If the state statute governing distributions in dissolution expressly requires the dissolving entity to transfer assets to other charities with purposes similar to the longstanding express purposes of the dissolving entity, the statute functionally embraces the static charter fidelity norm, at least in part. If the state statute does not explicitly require a dissolving entity to distribute assets only to a charitable transferee with specific purposes similar to those of the transferor, a court may be asked to decide whether to employ common law trust concepts to compel such a result.
}
