{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
C. Mission Fidelity Norms
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EPJBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EPJBI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
There is less precedent that directly and clearly articulates the mission fidelity norms. Mission fidelity norms have received at least modest judicial recognition, although it is difficult to discern their impact apart from charter 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_947_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_947_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*947
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 fidelity norms. The two types of norms are theoretically distinct because a charity\rquote s mission (for example, operating an elementary school) may be more specific than the purposes expressly articulated in the charity\rquote s corporate charter (for example, advancing charitable and educational purposes).
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EGKBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EGKBI_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
1. Support for the Historic Mission Fidelity Norm
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EQKBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EQKBI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
A few cases arguably embrace the historic mission fidelity norm, most notably in cases where a board seeks to devote funds to purposes that deviate from an entity\rquote s longstanding mission.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F201398601898_ID0EYKBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F201398601898_ID0EYKBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F201398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
201
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 For example, in 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Manhattan Eye
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, it was \u8220\'3faxiomatic that the Board of Directors is charged with the duty to ensure that the mission of the charitable corporation is carried out.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F202398601898_ID0EPLBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F202398601898_ID0EPLBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F202398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
202
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Further, the court opined that deviating \u8220\'3ffrom the charity\rquote s central and well-understood mission should be a carefully chosen option of last resort.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F203398601898_ID0E4LBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F203398601898_ID0E4LBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F203398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
203
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Taken at face value, these statements reflect adoption of the historic mission fidelity norm. However, it is unclear whether the court assigned significance to the historic mission fidelity norm apart from the static charter fidelity norm. In 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Manhattan Eye
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, the purposes clause of the charity\rquote s articles of incorporation articulated its specific mission, a fact that did not escape the attention of the court.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F204398601898_ID0EQMBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F204398601898_ID0EQMBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F204398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
204
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EXMBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EXMBI_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_948_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_948_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*948
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Queen of Angels
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 offers additional judicial support for historicm ission fidelity. After stating that the hospital\rquote s articles of incorporation alone were sufficient to impress donations with a charitable trust, the court buttressed its conclusion with the observation that Queen had actually operated a hospital throughout its history, represented to governmental taxing authorities that it was a hospital, and solicited public donations for hospital purposes.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F205398601898_ID0EONBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F205398601898_ID0EONBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F205398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
205
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The court concluded that Queen \u8220\'3fwas intended to and did operate a hospital and cannot, consistent with the trust imposed upon it, abandon the operation of the hospital business in favor of clinics.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F206398601898_ID0E3NBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F206398601898_ID0E3NBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F206398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
206
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Although this portion of the opinion was dictum, it reflects judicial acceptance of the historic mission fidelity norm as applied to the use of funds received and accumulated while the nonprofit was carrying out its traditional mission.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EFOBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EFOBI_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
2. Support for the Dynamic Mission Fidelity Norm
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EPOBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EPOBI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Not all cases support rigid adherence to a charitable corporation\rquote s historic mission, however. For example, 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Bethany Medical Center
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 tends to reject the historic mission fidelity norm. In 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Bethany Medical Center
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, the Conference argued that Bethany should be dissolved under state law because it had \u8220\'3fcontracted away its purpose\u8221\'3f by selling hospital assets.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F207398601898_ID0EPPBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F207398601898_ID0EPPBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F207398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
207
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The Kansas Supreme Court disagreed, reasoning that the sale did not devoid Bethany of purpose because operating a hospital was \u8220\'3fonly one of several health-care related purposes pursued by Bethany.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F208398601898_ID0E3PBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F208398601898_ID0E3PBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F208398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
208
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EDQBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EDQBI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Similarly, the court in 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Hughes Springs
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 held that the doctrine of cy pres did not prohibit a nonprofit corporation originally formed to operate an ambulance service from amending its purposes so as \u8220\'3fto provide various services to the community which relate to the health and safety of the citizens in the Hughes Springs area.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F209398601898_ID0E4QBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F209398601898_ID0E4QBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F209398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
209
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The court also refused to order dissolution of the corporation, for it was perfectly capable of fulfilling its amended purposes.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F210398601898_ID0ECRBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F210398601898_ID0ECRBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F210398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
210
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 By endorsing the legitimacy of the corporation\rquote s use of assets to further its amended charter purposes, the court rejected both the static charter fidelity norm and the historic mission fidelity norm.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0ELRBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0ELRBI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Although these cases reject the historic mission fidelity norm, they do not necessarily embrace the dynamic mission fidelity norm. Affirming the 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_949_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_949_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*949
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 dynamic mission fidelity norm not only imposes an affirmative obligation to advance the charity\rquote s specific mission upon charity fiduciaries, but also allows the governing board to amend the mission.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F211398601898_ID0E2RBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F211398601898_ID0E2RBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F211398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
211
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Some language in case law tends to support this approach,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F212398601898_ID0E5RBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F212398601898_ID0E5RBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F212398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
212
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 but it is unclear whether existing authorities actually impose an obligation on charity fiduciaries to advance a charitable mission that is more specific than its charter purpose. Insofar as the PLNO recognizes both the utility of adopting mission statements and the need to evaluate grounds for altering a charity\rquote s mission over time, it at least partially embraces the dynamic mission fidelity norm.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F213398601898_ID0EFSBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F213398601898_ID0EFSBI_1}
