}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EMSBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EMSBI_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
D. The Charity Advancement Norm
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EWSBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EWSBI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
State law consistently supports the elementary charity advancement norm and its negative corollary. That it does so follows from the fundamental nature of charitable nonprofit corporations and the statutes authorizing them. Directors of a charitable nonprofit corporation must govern in a way that promotes compliance with the corporation\rquote s charter.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F214398601898_ID0EETBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F214398601898_ID0EETBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F214398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
214
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Accordingly, a nonprofit corporation organized for charitable purposes must advance \u8220\'3fcharitable,\u8221\'3f as opposed to non-charitable, purposes. Certainly, the typical nonprofit corporation statute authorizes a nonprofit corporation to have purposes broader than those that the law recognizes as \u8220\'3fcharitable.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F215398601898_ID0EMTBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F215398601898_ID0EMTBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F215398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
215
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 However, because corporations organized for charitable purposes are typically incorporated under nonprofit corporation statutes that require compliance with charter purposes, it is accurate to state that a charity\rquote s compliance with its charter requires that it serve a charitable purpose. Thus, the essential structure of the statutory law of nonprofit charitable corporations is designed to promote the charity advancement norm and its negative corollary.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EYTBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EYTBI_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
E. Summary
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0ECUBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0ECUBI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
State case law and statutes governing directors of nonprofit corporations clearly embrace the legality norm and the charity advancement norm, together 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_950_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_950_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*950
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 with its negative corollary. The status of other obedience norms governing charity fiduciaries varies among the states.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EWUBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EWUBI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
State laws embrace norms of charter fidelity, but they differ in whether they impose the static charter fidelity norm or the dynamic charter fidelity norm. Most states adopt the dynamic charter fidelity norm as applied solely to the formal ability of a governing board to amend the charity\rquote s governing instrument. But in other contexts, in which the question involves the freedom of directors to direct corporate assets to uses that differ from historic corporate purposes, the states take drastically different approaches. Some states rely on trust law principles and impose the static charter fidelity norm on directors, whereas others apply corporate law concepts broadly and hold directors to the dynamic charter fidelity norm. 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In one state, different courts have embraced different norms.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EOVBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EOVBI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Whether states impose some form of the mission fidelity norm that is independent of a charter fidelity norm is debatable. Some authorities appear to embrace the historic mission fidelity norm, but do so in contexts in which the norm largely coincides with the static charter fidelity norm. Other judicial authorities reject the historic mission fidelity norm, but fall short of clearly embracing the dynamic mission fidelity norm.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EAWBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EAWBI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Reform efforts have not resolved the states\rquote  differing approaches. The RMNCA and the MNCA Third do not wrestle with the difficult issues raised by the choice of obedience norms. The PLNO embraces the dynamic charter fidelity norm and offers some support for the dynamic mission fidelity norm. States have yet to look to the PLNO for guidance on these issues, however.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EVWBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EVWBI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
This survey of the law of obedience norms governing charity fiduciaries suggests the importance of identifying the precise purposes that obedience norms serve. Before one can determine \u8220\'3fwhat\u8221\'3f obedience norms should govern, one must ponder \u8220\'3fwhy\u8221\'3f we need them.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EEXBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EEXBI_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
IV. 
}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
The Purpose of Obedience Norms
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EPXBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EPXBI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The major justifications for obedience norms can be categorized as follows: (1) ensuring the presence of public benefit,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F216398601898_ID0EVXBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F216398601898_ID0EVXBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F216398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
216
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (2) promoting equity,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F217398601898_ID0EYXBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F217398601898_ID0EYXBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F217398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
217
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 and (3) encouraging efficiency.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F218398601898_ID0E3XBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F218398601898_ID0E3XBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F218398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
218
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EDYBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EDYBI_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
A. Public Benefit
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0ENYBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0ENYBI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Ensuring that charitable organizations benefit the public is the most basic 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_951_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_951_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*951
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 purpose of obedience norms.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F219398601898_ID0E1YBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F219398601898_ID0E1YBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F219398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
219
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 In fact, the law defines a \u8220\'3f\u8220\'3fcharitable purpose\u8221\'3f as one that is beneficial to the public.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F220398601898_ID0E6YBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F220398601898_ID0E6YBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F220398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
220
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 To require fiduciaries to advance \u8220\'3fcharitable\u8221\'3f purposes is therefore an attempt to promote public benefit. Of course, requiring fiduciaries to advance charitable purposes (and not others) is the essence of the charity advancement norm and its negative corollary. Additionally, the legality norm generally complements the charity advancement norm by discouraging behavior deemed detrimental to the public. Thus, the public benefit justification for obedience norms supports adoption of the charity advancement norm and its negative corollary, and supports imposition of the legality norm as well.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0ERZBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0ERZBI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
A more difficult question is whether the public benefit justification supports the adoption of additional obedience norms. Charter fidelity norms reinforce the charity advancement norm by reminding fiduciaries of the activities that they can and cannot cause their charities to undertake. Although the charity advancement norm may be sufficient in theory to ensure that a charity produces public benefit,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F221398601898_ID0E4ZBI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F221398601898_ID0E4ZBI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F221398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
221
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 some form of charter fidelity norm is useful in prompting charity fiduciaries to adhere to the charity advancement norm. A similar argument can be made in favor of the mission fidelity norm, because requiring governance in accordance with a mission focuses attention on advancing charity thoughtfully. The dynamic fidelity norms would serve these functions just as well as the static norms, however.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EM1BI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EM1BI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Indeed, it is doubtful that the public benefit justification requires adoption of any \u8220\'3fstatic\u8221\'3f obedience norm (static charter fidelity or historic mission fidelity). Substantive government approval of an entity\rquote s choice of charitable purpose and mission is generally not required upon formation of a charitable entity.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F222398601898_ID0EX1BI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F222398601898_ID0EX1BI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F222398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
222
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 A plausible explanation for this reality is that the law recognizes that the choice of charitable purpose by private actors suffices to promote public benefit if it is assumed that pursuing 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
any
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 charitable purpose produces public benefit. 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Why, then, should substantive, ex ante governmental approval be necessary to ensure the presence of public benefit when an entity\rquote s governing board decides to alter charitable purpose or mission? One can articulate 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_952_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_952_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*952
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (questionable) justifications grounded in equity and efficiency for such approval, but ensuring the presence of some public benefit does not seem a persuasive justification for either static norm.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EN2BI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EN2BI_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
B. Equity
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EX2BI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EX2BI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Another possible justification for obedience norms is that they promote equity by protecting the reliance interests of donors, and perhaps other stakeholders.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F223398601898_ID0E62BI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F223398601898_ID0E62BI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F223398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
223
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The theory is that donors have donated funds to charitable entities under the assumption that the money will be used to perform the donee\rquote s charitable purposes as they exist when the funds are received.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F224398601898_ID0EE3BI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F224398601898_ID0EE3BI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F224398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
224
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 To allow the charity to alter its purposes, or perhaps even mission, after receiving such donations is unfair to those donors because of their reliance on the then-existing purposes/mission of the donee. This rationale appears to be a favorite of the courts and commentators embracing static obedience norms.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F225398601898_ID0EM3BI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F225398601898_ID0EM3BI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F225398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
225
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 However, the equity rationale has limited appeal in the case of charitable trusts, and considerably less persuasive force as applied to charitable nonprofit corporations. Further, the reliance-based equity justification does not support all obedience norms equally, even in the case of charitable trusts.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EY3BI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EY3BI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Because of long-standing legal deference to the terms of trusts in general
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F226398601898_ID0E53BI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F226398601898_ID0E53BI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F226398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
226
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 and the application of the doctrine of cy pres to charitable trusts,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F227398601898_ID0EB4BI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F227398601898_ID0EB4BI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F227398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
227
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 those who currently contribute to charitable trusts properly assume that the trust\rquote s express charitable purposes will typically remain unchanged. But this general observation justifies upholding donors\rquote  reliance interests on equity grounds only for as long as the law continues to apply cy pres or some similar doctrine. Were the law to change, those who subsequently donate to charitable trusts would lack a compelling reliance interest in static charter fidelity.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F228398601898_ID0EM4BI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F228398601898_ID0EM4BI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F228398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
228
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Further, even under current law, those who donate to charitable trusts properly assume 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_953_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_953_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*953
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 that the static charter fidelity norm applies only when the terms of trust do not authorize amendments by the trustees. If the terms of trust provide a mechanism for the trustees to amend the trust terms without judicial proceedings, those terms control.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F229398601898_ID0EZ4BI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F229398601898_ID0EZ4BI_1}
