229
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 A donor who gives to a charitable trust that permits amendments to its purposes clause therefore has no strong reliance interest in the fixed terms of trust.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F230398601898_ID0E44BI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F230398601898_ID0E44BI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F230398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
230
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EE5BI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EE5BI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Moreover, even in the case of a charitable trust that does not provide for amendments by trustees, trust law does not support adoption of the historic mission fidelity norm. The classic expression of the duty to obey terms of trust that the law imposes on trustees applies only with respect to the actual 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
terms of trust
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
. An action in cy pres is necessary to alter charitable purposes only when administering the 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
terms of trust
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 becomes impossible, illegal, impracticable, or wasteful.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F231398601898_ID0EW5BI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F231398601898_ID0EW5BI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F231398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
231
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The classic articulation of cy pres does not require trustees of charitable trusts to go to court to bless a new charitable mission that falls within the express charitable purposes of the trust.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F232398601898_ID0E25BI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F232398601898_ID0E25BI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F232398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
232
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Hence, donors to a charitable trust have no strong reliance interest in any particular charitable mission of a trust when other charitable missions would also further express the trust\rquote s purposes.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EE6BI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EE6BI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Reliance-based equity offers an even less compelling justification for static obedience norms in the case of charitable corporations. 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Nonprofit corporation statutes typically enable charter amendments without court approval,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F233398601898_ID0EN6BI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F233398601898_ID0EN6BI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F233398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
233
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 immediately distinguishing them from charitable trusts, which are governed by default rules requiring court approval of amendments to a trust instrument.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F234398601898_ID0ES6BI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F234398601898_ID0ES6BI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F234398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
234
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Donors to charitable nonprofit corporations are on notice of these corporate laws. It is plausible that the average donor would assume that static obedience norms do not govern directors of charitable nonprofit corporations, perhaps even as applied to their power to deploy existing assets to advance new charitable purposes.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F235398601898_ID0E16BI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F235398601898_ID0E16BI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F235398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
235
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 If donors do assume such flexibility, rejection of static obedience norms does not defeat their reliance interests.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EDACI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EDACI_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_954_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_954_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*954
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Moreover, if the law across the states consistently assumed contrary donor expectations, counsel to nonprofit charitable corporations could draft governing documents to undermine the basis for maintaining the assumption.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F236398601898_ID0EPACI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F236398601898_ID0EPACI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F236398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
236
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Lawyers could draft broadly phrased purposes clauses in corporate charters so as to limit the constraining effect of the static charter fidelity norm. They could also draft charter provisions explicitly stating that directors can deploy existing assets to advance newly amended charitable purposes. Under these circumstances, donors presumed to be aware of these provisions would have no legitimate basis for believing that their donations will be used to further any particular charitable purpose or mission. All of these charter provisions should be enforceable,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F237398601898_ID0E2ACI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F237398601898_ID0E2ACI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F237398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
237
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 which would undermine the reliance-based equity argument used to justify static obedience norms.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EEBCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EEBCI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Furthermore, adopting the historic mission fidelity norm as applied to directors of nonprofit charitable corporations would be doctrinally suspect. The historic mission fidelity norm traditionally has not been imposed on trustees of charitable trusts independently of the static charter fidelity norm.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F238398601898_ID0EPBCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F238398601898_ID0EPBCI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F238398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
238
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Declining to shackle trustees of charitable trusts with this norm while at the same time imposing it on directors of nonprofit corporations (who oversee a form of entity that, if anything, is usually thought to avoid some of the rigidities of the law of charitable trusts) creates incoherence.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F239398601898_ID0EUBCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F239398601898_ID0EUBCI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F239398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
239
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 A possible response to this line of reasoning is that a single settlor of a charitable trust has only herself to blame for failing to articulate a precise charitable mission, whereas the multitudinous donors to a charitable corporation operating perpetually have no ability to draft charter purposes. But this objection is largely illusory. Rejecting the static charter fidelity norm and the historic mission fidelity norm in the case of charitable nonprofit corporations does not leave donors without protections analogous to those enjoyed by the settlor of a charitable trust. Donors of charitable corporations are still free to protect their donations from diversion to an alternative charitable use in the future by 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_955_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_955_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*955
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 explicitly restricting their gifts when made.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F240398601898_ID0EHCCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F240398601898_ID0EHCCI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F240398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
240
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The law generally honors such restrictions.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F241398601898_ID0EMCCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F241398601898_ID0EMCCI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F241398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
241
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Consequently, donors who wish to bind charitable donees to fulfill their expectations can do so.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EVCCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EVCCI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Additionally, rejecting the static obedience norms in the case of charitable corporations does not disregard donor expectations altogether. It is possible to disfavor a system requiring ex ante, substantive governmental approval of a change in a charitable corporation\rquote s purpose or mission while embracing a system that provides for meaningful ex post judicial review of fiduciary decisions to change purposes or mission. 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
A variety of approaches short of ex ante, substantive governmental approval would balance the reliance interest of donors and the desirability of vesting in nonprofit directors the primary responsibility for altering a charitable corporation\rquote s course.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F242398601898_ID0ECDCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F242398601898_ID0ECDCI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F242398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
242
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EJDCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EJDCI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Finally, the basic charity advancement norm and its negative corollary protect the most compelling reliance interest of donors and other stakeholders. Although it is debatable whether a charitable corporation\rquote s donors should assume that the donee will not unilaterally alter its charitable purposes or mission, donors surely are entitled to assume that the donee will not divert funds to a 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
non-charitable
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 purpose. Such diversion would plainly violate donors\rquote  expectations. Fiduciaries who comply with the fundamental charity advancement norm and its negative corollary honor this reasonable expectation of donors. Thus, once again, rejecting static obedience norms does not require rejecting all reliance interests of donors.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EDECI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EDECI_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
C. Efficiency
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0ENECI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0ENECI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
One may also attempt to justify obedience norms on grounds of efficiency.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F243398601898_ID0EVECI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F243398601898_ID0EVECI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F243398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
243
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The charity advancement norm is limited in the degree to which it promotes efficiency because compliance with the norm merely means that fiduciaries are furthering some charitable purpose, not that they are doing so 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_956_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_956_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*956
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 effectively.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F244398601898_ID0E6ECI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F244398601898_ID0E6ECI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F244398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
244
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Charter fidelity norms may promote efficiency by educating and reminding charity fiduciaries to adhere to the charity advancement norm and its negative corollary. Moreover, requiring some form of mission fidelity is also likely to be efficient, insofar as requiring governance in accordance with the charity\rquote s mission encourages fiduciaries to deliberate and weigh possible goals and achievable outcomes, rather than merely supervise random acts of kindness.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F245398601898_ID0EHFCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F245398601898_ID0EHFCI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F245398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
245
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 However, the dynamic charter and mission fidelity norms would serve these functions just as well as the static norms. Furthermore, there are valid reasons to believe that static obedience norms, on balance, are probably less efficient than dynamic norms in the case of charitable corporations.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F246398601898_ID0EOFCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F246398601898_ID0EOFCI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F246398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
246
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EVFCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EVFCI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Short-term efficiency is better served by imposing dynamic norms in some contexts.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F247398601898_ID0E4FCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F247398601898_ID0E4FCI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F247398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
247
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 To illustrate, consider a cash-rich charity organized to fund the neutering of stray cats in Louisiana cities. Assume a hurricane blasts through the Gulf of Mexico and leaves thousands homeless in New Orleans. The social welfare produced by helping homeless human hurricane victims surely outweighs that of neutering the (now drastically diminished) feline population. However, the static charter fidelity norm and the historic mission fidelity norm would limit the charity\rquote s ability to quickly alleviate widespread human suffering because of the inevitable delay caused by the requirement mandating that the charity obtain ex ante government approval of the change in charitable purpose.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F248398601898_ID0EKGCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F248398601898_ID0EKGCI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F248398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
248
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0ERGCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0ERGCI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The efficiency of requiring ex ante substantive governmental approval of changes in charter purpose and mission that are less time sensitive depends on many factors, including the out-of-pocket costs of such a system, the relative competence of charity fiduciaries and government agents in exercising judgment, and the long-term effect of the choice of the system on charitable donations.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F249398601898_ID0EYGCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F249398601898_ID0EYGCI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F249398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
249
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E6GCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E6GCI_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_957_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_957_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*957
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The costs associated with the first factor, out-of-pocket costs of obtaining ex ante substantive governmental approval to change the charter purpose or mission, are likely higher than the costs of a system that does not require such approval. Government actors will likely review fewer changes in a system that does not require ex ante substantive government approval.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F250398601898_ID0EOHCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F250398601898_ID0EOHCI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F250398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
250
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 No credible argument can be made that requiring a governmental actor to review and evaluate every change in charter purpose or mission by every charity is cheap. Furthermore, other costs must be considered. For example, nonprofits seeking to alter their charitable paths will incur advocacy costs.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
