\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EGSCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EGSCI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Ultimately, two questions persist. The primary purpose of articulating these last two questions is not to answer them here, but to suggest how courts and state legislatures should think through the issues in order to answer them. As to the penultimate question, those convinced that charity directors and trustees are uniquely well suited to assess the merits of changes in purposes and mission may favor one of two standards of judicial review. One standard would accord heightened deference to charity managers, perhaps by authorizing courts to find a violation of fiduciary duty only when managers have acted arbitrarily and capriciously. Those who see no real difference between a fiduciary\rquote s judgment concerning charitable purposes and mission and that concerning any other matter may favor another approach to judicial review, one that evaluates all disinterested exercises of fiduciary discretion under the same standard.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F269398601898_ID0E1SCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F269398601898_ID0E1SCI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F269398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
269
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Those who desire heightened protection of the reliance interests of donors and other stakeholders might favor a standard of judicial review that places an affirmative burden on charity fiduciaries to establish the justification for a change in purposes or mission.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F270398601898_ID0E5SCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F270398601898_ID0E5SCI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F270398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
270
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EFTCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EFTCI_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_962_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_962_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*962
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Although the issue of what standard of judicial review should apply in these cases is theoretically distinct from the issue of whether such review should be ex ante or ex post, a standard of judicial review that accords some deference to the judgment of fiduciaries appears to be consistent with the assumptions that would lead one to favor dynamic obedience norms over static norms.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F271398601898_ID0ERTCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F271398601898_ID0ERTCI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F271398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
271
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The argument for applying dynamic obedience norms to directors of charitable corporations ultimately implies that charitable boards are better suited than courts and attorneys general to monitor and redirect charitable paths. If that premise is correct, some degree of judicial deference to the decisions of directors is warranted.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E4TCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E4TCI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Concerning the final question, state law should articulate the grounds that justify the decision of charity fiduciaries to change a charity\rquote s purposes and mission, regardless of the standard of judicial review that is applied or whether such review is performed ex ante or ex post. The choice of grounds for justifying a change in purposes and mission is theoretically distinct from the decision of whether to implement ex ante or ex post judicial review of the change. Nonetheless, the two issues are intertwined. Those who favor static norms will likely desire to limit the grounds for changing a charity\rquote s purposes and mission,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F272398601898_ID0EMUCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F272398601898_ID0EMUCI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F272398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
272
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 whereas those who favor dynamic norms will likely advocate for broader grounds justifying change.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F273398601898_ID0EQUCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F273398601898_ID0EQUCI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F273398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
273
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EXUCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EXUCI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
To illustrate, the doctrine of cy pres, which governs charitable trusts, embraces quite narrow grounds for changing charitable purposes,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F274398601898_ID0E4UCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F274398601898_ID0E4UCI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F274398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
274
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 an unsurprising reality if one observes that the static charter fidelity norm governs charitable trusts.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F275398601898_ID0ECVCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F275398601898_ID0ECVCI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F275398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
275
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 But if one is persuaded by the argument of Part IV that 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_963_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_963_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*963
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 dynamic obedience norms should govern directors of charitable corporations, one should embrace a broader set of grounds for altering a corporate charity\rquote s purposes and mission and consequent deployment of assets than those recognized by the doctrine of cy pres. Relevant facts include (1) inefficiencies in maintaining the status quo (high operating costs, difficulty in retaining competent personnel, inability to maintain adequate facilities, etc.); (2) the ability of other institutions (government, nonprofits, and for-profit firms) to serve the community previously served by the charity desiring to change course; (3) the importance of the needs that would be met with the change in purpose relative to the needs currently being met; (4) the ability of other institutions to meet the needs that would be addressed with the change in purpose; and (5) the efficiency with which the charity could pursue the new purpose.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F276398601898_ID0ERVCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F276398601898_ID0ERVCI_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F276398601898_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
276
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EYVCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EYVCI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Although these factors bear upon the reasonableness of a decision to change a charity\rquote s purposes, it is most important to emphasize (1) that the law must be clear, so that both fiduciaries and governmental actors know what is expected of charity fiduciaries, and (2) that the adoption of dynamic obedience norms suggests a measure of confidence in the decision-making capacity of fiduciarie, confidence that implies their ability to evaluate all of the relevant facts. Courts and legislatures should keep these points in mind as they impose obedience norms on charity fiduciaries.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EHWCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EHWCI_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
VI. 
}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
Conclusion and Implications
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0ESWCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0ESWCI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The law of obedience norms governing charity fiduciaries is far from settled and coherent. State laws embrace the legality norm and the charity advancement norm, and some form of charter fidelity norm. 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The static charter fidelity norm governs charitable trusts by default. Many states appear to accept the dynamic charter fidelity norm as applied strictly to the formal requirements for amending a charitable corporation\rquote s articles of incorporation. However, states differ in the constraints that they impose on corporate directors seeking to deploy charitable assets for purposes other than those traditionally served by their charities. Some states clearly implement the static charter fidelity norm in these contexts, whereas others favor the dynamic charter fidelity norm. The law is ordinarily unclear as to whether charity fiduciaries must advance a charitable mission more specific than its charter purpose(s).
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EQXCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EQXCI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
An analysis of the potential justifications for obedience norms affirms the legitimacy of the charity advancement norm and its negative corollary, as well as (in general) the legality norm. The efficiency justifications for broadly 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1530_964_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1530_964_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*964
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 imposing the static charter fidelity norm on trustees of charitable trusts are plausible, though not definitive. However, dynamic charter fidelity norms should apply to directors of charitable corporations. The historic mission fidelity norm, as a norm independent of charter fidelity, should not apply to charity fiduciaries. Rather, imposing the dynamic mission fidelity norm on all charity fiduciaries, both directors and trustees, is sensible.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0ENYCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0ENYCI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Deciding what norms should govern which charity fiduciaries does not complete the necessary analysis. States must also decide the degree of deference that courts should extend to the decisions of charity fiduciaries, and must determine the grounds that justify a decision by charity fiduciaries to change a charity\rquote s purposes and mission. This Article suggests how states should approach these design questions.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E6YCI_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E6YCI_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
This Article does not focus on whether the law\rquote s implementation of obedience norms should occur through imposition of a \u8220\'3fduty of obedience\u8221\'3f on directors of charitable nonprofit corporations, in addition to the duties of care and loyalty. Nevertheless, this Article\rquote s analysis suggests that the tentative draft of the PLNO strikes the proper balance by recognizing the legitimacy of certain obedience norms, yet declining to articulate a distinct \u8220\'3fduty of obedience\u8221\'3f governing charity fiduciaries. The dynamic charter fidelity norm and the dynamic mission fidelity norm are best implemented in a system that confers on charity fiduciaries both primary responsibility for forging a charity\rquote s path and discretion in how best to do so. The twin fiduciary duties of care and loyalty, exercised in good faith, provide sufficient standards for evaluating directors\rquote  decisions under such a system. To impose an additional \u8220\'3fduty of obedience\u8221\'3f on directors arguably implies that decisions concerning mission and purpose are somehow much different from other exercises of discretion. It is doubtful that they are, and therefore doubtful that they favor the more traditional expression of fiduciary duties.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
}
